Environment minister Barbara Creecy says the SA Weather Service issued warnings in the days leading up to the devastating floods in KwaZulu-Natal. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Environment minister Barbara Creecy says the SA Weather Service issued warnings in the days leading up to the devastating floods in KwaZulu-Natal. The minister was defending the SAWS following reports that weather stations are deteriorating due to a lack of funding. READ:Â Study: Climate change amplified KZN disaster Creecy says R100-million has been allocated to the weather service over three years to upgrade infrastructure. "There is new technology available which can predict severe storms and we would want to upgrade our radar technology to have access to that, so that we can be more accurate in indicating the geographic location that these events would target," she said. "We are also working on areas where there has been vandalism of our equipment. We are moving them from the side of the road, into police stations and school premises so that it is safe from being vandalised."